description:
Grab the new PAPER LAUNCH shirt in 100% cotton here! https://store.gamersnexus.net/products/paper-launch-cotton or Tri-Blend here! https://store.gamersnexus.net/products/paper-launch-triblend
This is our review and benchmark of the NVIDIA GeForce RTX 5060 Ti 16GB GPU, so at least you'll have numbers if this situation ever becomes sane again. Right now though, we just don't see where you buy a card unless truly in need as the pricing situation is out of control across all tiers, used and new alike. We benchmarked the RTX 5060 Ti vs. the RTX 4060 Ti 8GB, the RTX 3070 Ti, 3080, RX 9070, RX 7600, and dozens more video cards to test the performance of something that will ultimately be leveraged by parasites.

Like our content? Please consider becoming our Patron to support us: http://www.patreon.com/gamersnexus

TIMESTAMPS

Links to Amazon and Newegg are typically monetized on our channel (affiliate links) and may return a commission of sales to us from the retailer. This is unrelated to the product manufacturer. Any advertisements or sponsorships are disclosed within the video ("this video is brought to you by") and above the fold in the description. We do not ever produce paid content or "sponsored content" (meaning that the content is our idea and is not funded externally aside from whatever ad placement is in the beginning) and we do not ever charge manufacturers for coverage.

comments.text: I'm hoping you guys will actually care about this: When averaging performance over N games, it's more meaningful to use a geometric mean than an (arithmetic) mean/average as that preserves the % better/% worse relationships. It also means that you get the same results whether comparing fps or ms/frame. For example for 16 games, calculate by multiplying the 16 values and taking the 16th root (or square root 4 times). Using the sum/N averages higher weighting of differences in games that produce higher fps when actually it's probably the games giving lower fps that matter more (or at least as much). I don't know how your calculations are generally done and noting this just in case.

comments.text:
OK, I'm currently sitting on a 2070 Super, so it's kind of long in the tooth. Problem is I want something that can at least double the performance, preferably triple it. With three generations between them that shouldn't be a problem, right? Well the 5060 Ti foes about double the performance, better than that in RT, something I haven't bothered with before, but now new games are starting to require RT to run so it's becoming more important. Next up it the monitor. I'm currently on a 1440p monitor and quite happy about the resolution, but the GPU is just to weak for this right now. Having run 1440p I'm uncertain about 4K. With my eyesight it doesn't really make a difference, but a lot of older games and even parts of Windows just don't rescale worth a damn. So I'm tottering on the question about resolution for now.
Anyway, to me, the 5060 has a few really irritating faults. First of it's a nVidia GPU and they have been irritating me the last few years. Then there's the price. Now I haven't seen a 5060 for sale yet so I really don't know how the prices will turn lut, but knowing nVidia I'm guessing the MSRP will be just as much a joke as it's been for all the other 50 series cards. And they stopped supporting PhysX for 32-bit applications. And that's something I hate. Now they've released the source code, or at least I think they have, so there is a slim chance that someone will find a way to make it work. Finally the RTX 5060 Ti is barely twice as fast as the 2070 in most of the tested games.

So how is the alternatives then? Well the RX 9060 has not been released yet so we doesn't have benchmask scores for it yet. But what looks more interesting is the RTX 5070 Ti and the RX 9070 XT. But they are pretty pricey. The positives are that the performance is over twice the performance of my old 2070, often closer to three times the performance. 

But there's negatives also. The RTX 5070 Ti is nVidia based And that's a negative now. -To make it worse it only has 12GB video memory, and that's not optimal for a modern GPU.-- 

The RX 907+ XT also has a few negatives. AMD has not been as active making user tools like NVIDIA Broadcast. And amazingly enough I really like that little bunch of tools. Mostly I just use the filtering to take care of funky microphone hiss when talking on Discort, but it's extremly good at that and I would hate to not have it available. Then there's the Video encoder. I don't use it much, but there's no question that NVENC is a lot better than the AMD alternative. Now it's actually just used for capturing game video. And reencoding I do using software solutions as they are better than NVENC. And yes I've done tests so it's not just repeating some gearheads posts. But again, I would hate going to a worse quality solution for the video capture. Now I am aware that PhysX are not supported by AMD graphics cards. But then it never were so this gen doesn't lack something that earlier generations did support.
Finally it's the price and performance that makes this a tough decision. I think it was yesterday I looked at the price and performance of the 5070 Ti and 9050 XT. Using data from another channel that had benchmarked I think 20 or 21 games, the average speed had the 5070 Ti showing a FPS advantage of about... And darn it I can't remember the exact percentage. But it was just a little faster and cost just a little more locally. Actually the price difference in percentage was lower than the price difference in percentage. In other words the 5070 Ti cost was more than worth it when looking at price/performance. Still I don't want to put more money into the pockets of nVidia. Another frustrating thing is that the 7900 XTX is still besting the 9070 XT and the 5060 Ti. It actually usually is just a hair slower than the 4090 and a little faster than the 5080, and it doesn't cost that much more than a 9070 XT. A friend of mine bought one a few months ago and it was then cheaper than a 9070 XT is today. Now that is not helping AMD sell me on the 9070 XT.
Unfortunately the 7900 XTX is now just a hair more expensive than the RTX 5070 Ti. And that's when it's available at all. They are getting hard to get these days.

Edit: Added the strike through as that was a mistake. The RTX 5070 does only have 12GB of memory while the 5070 Ti has 16GB...

comments.text:
You won't read this but please drop the idea of comparing a GPU die size to that of the series flagship, it's simply incorrect to compare GPUs not on their actual specs but instead by how they compare to a massive overpriced flagship that no one should ever buy. Instead it's better to compare to previous cards specs and competitors specs to see what "Class" it is.

Instead something like this makes more sense
1050Ti: 132mm2 128-bit
5060Ti: 182mm2 128-bit
1060-6GB: 200mm2 192-bit
which would put the 5060Ti is being between a 50Ti and 60 by 10 series standards. You can even use it to evaluate a cards "Class" by the standards of whichever generation you want.

Evaluating a card by it's relative cuda core count to a 5090 type card is going to result in weird and incorrect conclusions because of how large and expensive the die is.

comments.text:
I get the idea that used 30 series makes sense performance wise at their current market price, but the problem is this generation of cards are out at the peak of GPU mining craze, and very little cards were actually in the hands of gamers. It's a much higher risk of those cards to die pretty early comparing to what we used to believe - used video cards can last long.

Because most if not all secondhand 30 series cards were heavily used 24x7 for mining. That's including those labeled as "new" - I mean, Nvidia stopped producing the silicon years ago, why would you believe there are "new" cards? Remember those cards were very valuable in the mining age, sold well beyond their price tags, it's very unlikely some unused inventory wasn't exposed during that age for the easy money.

If you're still considering getting a secondhand 30 series card, do your research and be ready for it to die on you soon. A card with a brand-new looking cooler doesn't mean the vram chips and/or core silicon weren't almost dead. Just as value doesn't mean anything when the MSRP on new cards are fake, value also doesn't mean anything for used cards if they die soon. If you can get it from someone you know bought the card brand-new back when it came out, then go for it. Other wise I suggest save up for a new card - buying a card dies in months is basically the same as throwing your money down the drain.

comments.text: Bus width shenanigans. More buses = more expensive, which is why it's always been the first thing to be reduced on budget cards. The 5060 and its variants have a 128 bit bus, but the 5070 has a 192 bit bus. You can attach 16 GB to a 128 bit bus, but not a 192 bit bus. The 5070 Ti has a 256 bus to make 16 GB possible, with an appropriate amount of bandwidth.

comments.text:
@ You can throw a wall of text, or you can go check out 3070 desktop vs 3070 laptop results.  I'd love to see where you were getting your results from as I couldn't find a 150w 3070 mobile that was getting much more than 5% faster than a desktop 3060.  Memory bandwidth has almost nothing to do with performance so long as it isnt being oversaturated with more data than the memory bus can transfer. 

Yes the 3060ti and 4060 differ as you increase resolution, but lets not act like it isnt an extra 3% over the lead at 1080p in HWUB's testing.  It is definitely outside margin of error, but certainly not something to write home about.

My 40% came from 115w variant numbers which are far more common than 150w variants.  So take it to 25-30% slower than the desktop variant for a 150w mobile version.  Your anecdotal experience with it is interesting, but can't be taken as fully correct given existing data available from Jarods tech.  You might be reaching stock 3060ti levels with some crazy undervolt, liquid metal and overclock...but your poor fans and TIM...

Good for you for having a vastly overperforming model?  To be clear, I'm not calling you a liar, but that perhaps your numbers simply arent as close as you think they are to a stock 3060ti.  

I've checked about 3 vids on 140-150w 3070's vs desktop 3070, another 3 on 3060ti vs 3070 and your numbers simply don't jive with the likes of jarrods tech, hwub, or daniel owens.

comments.text:
Vram is almost never the bottleneck in benchmarks once you have 8gb on 1080p, 12gb on 1440p/2k, and 16gb on 4k. The issues come from the real-game scenarios or extended play sessions that just don't show up in benchmarks as often. (Speaking specifically of the ingame self benchmarks; they need to be able to service their minimum required vram and the max on the market mostly equally)

With that acknowledged, i still agree that the graphs should mention it's the 16gb model, because layman users will absolutely not know any differences, but it shouldn't matter for most users. People playing at 4k are going to get better cards, and people at 1440p will be willing to drop from "ultra" textures to "high" if they run into the issues. I figure most hobbyist pc gamers are running 1080p, while the enthusiasts are doing 1440p or 4k

comments.text:
I felt nitpicky when I disliked the stupid RT introduction and marketing around it and DLSS with the 20 series. Super refresh didn't help. Prioritizing cryptobros and their ugly monkeys during COVID and lying about it made it easy for me to get a 6800XT. Which broke a long Nvidia streak. The 40 generation was no reason to pay attention and this generation is even worse. And Nvidia is again feeding silicon into a fraudulent tech bubble. And again it treats tech enthusiasts as pay pigs. And again it does underdeliver and rests their laurels on that stupid upscaler. Only this time they also let AI hallucinate frames and they are basing they marketing again on those crutches. Frame generation and upscaling is not a feature on a discrete graphics card at this price point. It makes sense on a 15W handheld. It makes no sense whatsoever on a 600 bucks card drawing over 150W. DLSS and frame gen are not features. They are the fig-leaf intended to lampshade the fact that 4 generations in Nvidia still can't deliver on their RT marketing for the 20 series. Rasterisation uplift also is laughable.
AMD will also win this if they set their ambitions to achieve mediocrity. Again. 
All of this is going to be a moot point within the US because with tariffs hitting and the headache involved, these cards will be shipped elsewhere. And the few that will be in the country will cost 2000 bucks. The US will have to make those 3080s last as long as Brazil made the Sega Genesis last.
Hard to say who is providing the most excrement flung into the fan. And on the Nvidia side, that is damn impressive given who their opponent is at the shit competition.
Time to recognize the patterns and ditch the shit-merchants.

comments.author: @JABelms

comments.text:
@JABelms It is not that simple anymore. Yes in many past titles 1080p with 8gb is fine but there are now newer titles where even at 1080p 8gb of Vram is eaten alive resulting in severe performance loss for the lack of additional memory.  

This is because games are now regularly shipping with 2 to 4K textures and if you don't have sufficient Vram or god forbid you don't have sufficient Vram AND you have a slower memory controller with a narrow bus then it can cause major stuttering on certain titles to the point of rendering them functionally unplayable even at 1080p

I mean look at intel Arc B580, that is a bottom of the pile bargain basement GPU,   how much Vram does it come with?  12Gb.  For the reasons I just stated.

So I say again, there is absolutely, 100%, no excuse for any company to be releasing an 8gb GPU in 2025 other than that company are greedy profiteering bastards selling inferior products to the less than correctly informed. 12Gb should be the minimum standard today, 16gb should be on the 70 series, 24gb on the 80 series and 32 on the 90 series, with other manufacturers following suit. Indeed AMD is always vastly more generous with Vram.


It is even more insulting for Nvidia to be selling 8gb cards once you realise Vram is actually cheap per module at $5 per gig for GDDR7. You are talking an extra 20 dollars in cost for a 12gb vs 8gb, 40 dollars in cost for 16gb vs 8gb which most people would be more than happy to pay that additional cost to have a graphics card that has a longer lifespan which 8gb cards do not.

I have a 3070,  it was a decent card, apart from its crap 8gb Vram which means I have to downscale certain games on my 1440p 144hz widescreen monitor, to 1080p, which is f**king depressing for a card that cost me $700 just three years ago making it functionally junk for my purposes today when if Nvidia had just not been such complete cheapskates and put 12gb on it and 16gb on the 3080 then they would have had much longer useful lifespans. There are even the odd examples of extreme modded 3070 and 3080 cards that have had additional Vram added and the performance uplift is crazy.

Even Jay agree's with me if curious:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cBeQWEtBB0k
